# PHASE 7 — Topic 2: Incremental Load Strategy

## 1. Explanation

An **Incremental Load Strategy** loads only the new or changed records from the source system into the target system.

Instead of reloading the full dataset, the pipeline identifies:

* inserted records
* updated records
* sometimes deleted records

This is usually done using:

* timestamps
* CDC (Change Data Capture)
* version columns
* audit columns

Process:

Source Table → Detect Changed Data → Load Only Changes

Purpose:
Reduce processing time and improve scalability.

---

## 2. Example

A customer table contains 10 million records.

Today:

* 5,000 new customers added
* 2,000 customer records updated

Incremental loading processes only those 7,000 changed records instead of all 10 million rows.

---

## 3. Use Cases

### Use Case 1 — Daily Enterprise ETL Pipelines

Large warehouses load only changed transactional data every day.

---

### Use Case 2 — Real-Time Data Synchronization

Streaming systems continuously load newly arriving events incrementally.

---

## 4. Advantages

### Advantage 1 — Faster Processing

Only changed records are processed, reducing execution time.

---

### Advantage 2 — Better Scalability

Efficient for very large datasets and enterprise systems.

---

## 5. Disadvantages

### Disadvantage 1 — More Complex Logic

Requires change tracking mechanisms and proper synchronization handling.

---

### Disadvantage 2 — Risk of Missing Changes

Incorrect timestamps or tracking failures may skip records.
